<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="87" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1844,1869]" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet, 
<emphasis box="[580,648,1845,1868]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">
<taxonomicName box="[580,645,1845,1868]" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Peltopsilopa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acuta">acuta</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
is a Latin adjective meaning pointed and refers to the sharply point apex of the presurstylus of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="88" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,2013]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,392]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="88" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1916,1941]" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Savaris &amp; Marinoni &amp; Mathis" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Savaris &amp; Marinoni &amp; Mathis" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[709,899,1916,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Peltopsilopa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anisotomoides">
<emphasis box="[709,899,1916,1941]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">P. anisotomoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
primarily by the shape of structures of the male terminalia (see key and figures). In addition, we have noted that the contrasted coloration of the scutum (deep, navy blue) as opposed to the scutellum (brownish blue) of this species is potentially useful although we have noted some variation. Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Savaris &amp; Marinoni &amp; Mathis" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Savaris &amp; Marinoni &amp; Mathis" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[426,615,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Peltopsilopa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anisotomoides">
<emphasis box="[426,615,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">P. anisotomoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tend to have a unicolorous mesonotum. Likewise, this species has more scutellar setulae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">We did not include the specimens from Costa Rica and Panamá in the type series because we lacked a male for dissection and species confirmation. Although not paratypes, we are confident of their conspecificity based on the external characters we discovered and that are included in the diagnosis. We observed that these specimens have conspicuous rows of scutellar setulae, which may be intraspecific variation or perhaps they represent specimens that did not have these setulae broken and missing.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
